  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1665833968" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1665833968" />
    <a title="Bruce" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2527793-bruce"><img alt="Bruce" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1289004291p2/2527793.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1665833968?book_show_action=true">Jun 11, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bruce" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bruce" href="/user/show/2527793-bruce">Bruce</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1665833968" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16277149988513766643">The edition I read of <i>Devices and Desires</i> was one of those tubby paperbacks with the glossy cover in bas relief which I avoid, assuming them to be formulaic thrillers, not detective novels. Ms. James does write real detective novels, and though the leisurely unfolding of the various subplots throughout 400 plus pages seemed verbose, I must admit these subplots satisfactorily dovetailed with each other, and contributed to the theme, which is the God-centered nature of human conscience. I was freq</span>
  <span id="freeText16277149988513766643" style="display:none">The edition I read of <i>Devices and Desires</i> was one of those tubby paperbacks with the glossy cover in bas relief which I avoid, assuming them to be formulaic thrillers, not detective novels. Ms. James does write real detective novels, and though the leisurely unfolding of the various subplots throughout 400 plus pages seemed verbose, I must admit these subplots satisfactorily dovetailed with each other, and contributed to the theme, which is the God-centered nature of human conscience. I was frequently moved by the elaboration of this theme, which resulted in substantive insight into the nitty-gritty struggle to act in accordance with one's conscience.<br /><br />My use of the adjective "leisurely" indicates the reason for a three star rating: its very length, no doubt made necessary by the meticulous plotting, inhibited a sense of dramatic urgency and suspense that would have so aptly complemented its story and theme.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16277149988513766643" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

